text: <https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/5313>

attachments.fallback: [w3c/csswg-drafts] #5313 [css-cascade] Clarify when an @import rule is valid
attachments.text:
<https://www.w3.org/TR/css-cascade-4/#at-import|The definition of when an `@import` rule is valid> is:

> Any `@import` rules must precede all other at-rules and style rules in a style sheet (besides `@charset`, which must be the first thing in the style sheet if it exists), or else the `@import` rule is invalid.

Given that in CSS3 `@charset` <https://www.w3.org/TR/css-syntax-3/#charset-rule|is no longer a rule>, it's not clear what the interpretation of that sentence would be when the parser finds an invalid rule named `@charset` that hasn't been interpreted as a fallback encoding marker by the input byte stream.

<https://github.com/andreubotella/css-import-validity-tests|I've run a few tests>, and the behavior of Firefox, Chrome and <https://wiki.gnome.org/Apps/Web/|Epiphany / GNOME Web> (a Webkit representative, since I don't have access to Mac or iOS machines) match: an `@import` rule is valid if every rule before it in the stylesheet is either invalid or an `@import` rule.

And this behavior is in fact consistent with <https://www.w3.org/TR/css-syntax-3/#css-stylesheets|this text in css-syntax>:

> If any style rule is invalid, or any at-rule is not recognized or is invalid according to its grammar or context, it’s a parse error. Discard that rule.

But in any case, the language in css-cascade should probably be updated to not refer to `@charset` as a rule and to clarify this, even if the correct behavior can be reasoned out from other specs.
